knowledge_graph.title: Chia seed
knowledge_graph.description: Chia seeds are the edible seeds of Salvia hispanica, a flowering plant in the mint family native to central and southern Mexico, or of the related Salvia columbariae, Salvia polystachia, or Salvia tiliifolia. Chia seeds are oval and gray with black and white spots, having a diameter of around 2 millimetres.

related_questions.question: What are the benefits of eating chia?
related_questions.snippet: Chia seed benefits Chia provides a similar amount of omega-3 fatty acids as ground flaxseed in the form of alpha linolenic acid, or ALA. They can help with weight loss. Chia seeds are an excellent source of fiber, which can improve heart health, reduce cholesterol levels and promote intestinal health.
related_questions.title: Chia seeds pack nutritional punch - Mayo Clinic Health System

related_questions.question: Do chia seeds reduce belly fat?
related_questions.snippet: Chia seeds are not a magic bullet for weight loss. They do not burn extra calories or increase metabolism in any way. Additionally, if you consume too many of them, you might gain weight instead.
related_questions.title: Chia Seed Water for Weight Loss: Does It Work? - Everyday Health

related_questions.question: Is it okay to eat chia seeds every day?
related_questions.snippet: Chia seeds are highly nutritious, boast a long list of health benefits and can be a healthy dietary addition for most. However, moderation is key, as eating too many may cause side effects. To prevent this, start with 1 ounce (28 grams) daily and assess your tolerance before slowly increasing your intake.
related_questions.title: Does Eating Too Many Chia Seeds Cause Side Effects? - Healthline

related_questions.question: How should chia seeds be eaten?
related_questions.snippet: Sprinkle a few teaspoons into breakfast cereal (hot or cold) salads, soups, or stews. Stir into salad dressings, sauces, marinades, or cake/muffin/bread batter. Use chia gel as a thickener added to smoothies, puddings, and soups (stir the gel into these foods after they are prepped or cooked).

buttons.subtitle: What Are Chia Seeds Good In
buttons.title: Chia seed benefits: What you need to know - Harvard Health
buttons.snippet: It's very easy to incorporate chia seeds into your diet. You can simply sprinkle a tablespoon or two on foods such as yogurt, cereal, or salads. You can add chia seeds to smoothies or soups, or mix them into pancake batter or another breakfast food.

buttons.subtitle: What Are The Side Effects Of Eating Chia Seeds
buttons.title: Are there side effects of eating too many chia seeds?
buttons.snippet: Eating too many chia seeds may cause side effects, such as digestive issues, allergic reactions, or weight gain. In moderation, however, chia seeds can be a nutritious addition to a balanced diet. Chia seeds are edible seeds that come from a plant belonging to the mint family, called Salvia hispanica.
snippet_highlighted_words: digestive issues, allergic reactions, or weight gain

buttons.subtitle: What Happens If You Eat Chia Seeds Every Day
buttons.title: Health Benefits of Chia Seeds - WebMD
buttons.snippet: Although chia seeds offer a variety of health benefits, eating too many may lead to complications: Digestive issues. Because of their high fiber content, eating too many chia seeds may cause constipation, diarrhea, bloating, and gas.

buttons.subtitle: What Other Benefits Do Chia Seeds Have
buttons.title: Chia Seeds 101: Nutrition Facts and Health Benefits - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Chia seeds contain large amounts of fiber and omega-3 fatty acids, plenty of protein, and many essential minerals and antioxidants. They may help improve digestive health, lower blood pressure, and improve blood sugar control. Chia seeds are the tiny black seeds of the chia plant (Salvia hispanica).
snippet_highlighted_words: improve digestive health, lower blood pressure, and improve blood sugar control

buttons.subtitle: How Much Chia Seeds Should I Eat Per Day
buttons.title: Can Eating Too Many Chia Seeds Cause Side Effects? - EatingWell
buttons.snippet: The Bottom Line These tiny seeds can provide fiber that helps lower cholesterol, boost your heart health and reduce your risk of developing chronic disease. That said, because chia seeds are packed with fiber and are calorie dense, stick with no more than 2 tablespoons per day.
snippet_highlighted_words: no more than 2 tablespoons per day

buttons.title: How Much Chia Seeds Should You Eat a Day? - MedicineNet
buttons.snippet: There is no RDA for chia seeds. Still, they can be safely eaten in amounts of 50 grams daily, which is about five tablespoons. Two tablespoons provide all of the nutritional benefits listed above.

buttons.snippet: “Chia seeds are high in fiber, which can increase satiety,” says Tara Collingwood, RDN, who is based in Orlando, Florida. They are also a good source of protein and fat, both of which are filling and may prevent overeating, she points out.
